00:04:21.394 --> 00:04:22.810
remember everything
that was said,

00:04:22.810 --> 00:04:24.160
but I'll back up a little bit.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:25.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:29.230
Just to remind you of
what you've heard before,

00:04:29.230 --> 00:04:32.620
to put everything in context.

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:36.160
The universe is very,
very big, and it's often

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:39.460
beyond the grasp of our
minds and our instruments.

00:04:39.460 --> 00:04:43.510
And so most of modern
cosmology doesn't even

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:45.280
date back 100 years.

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:47.320
And so you heard about Hubble.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:49.420
And Hubble was the
one who pointed out

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:52.660
that the universe doesn't have
just one galaxy, but billions

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:55.900
of galaxies by
resolving the stars

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:57.910
in the nebulae on the sky.

00:04:57.910 --> 00:05:02.120
And he also discovered that
the universe is expanding.

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:04.290
And probably Chris
and Father Guy

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:07.510
neglected to tell you that
Hubble got all of his degrees

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:08.992
at the University of Chicago.

00:05:08.992 --> 00:05:11.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:13.550
And I am required
to tell you that.

00:05:13.550 --> 00:05:14.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:14.490 --> 00:05:17.410
And I'll show you
Hubble's data here.

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:19.260
Some people think
that Hubble is famous

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:21.750
because here was
a bunch of coffee

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.150
stains on a piece
of graph paper,

00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:26.776
and he was able to draw a
straight line through it.

00:05:26.776 --> 00:05:28.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:30.660
But Hubble was a
great scientist.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:34.350
And Einstein played an
important role in this

00:05:34.350 --> 00:05:36.840
because without Einstein's
Theory of Gravity,

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:39.240
we wouldn't have the proper
interpretation for what's

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:40.440
going on.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:45.060
It's not that galaxies are
actually moving away from us,

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:47.430
it's that the
universe is expanding.

00:05:47.430 --> 00:05:51.390
So Einstein taught us that time
warps and space is flexible.

00:05:51.390 --> 00:05:53.670
And the best example
of space being flexible

00:05:53.670 --> 00:05:55.560
is the expansion
of the universe.

00:05:55.560 --> 00:05:58.170
And so the galaxies are
just moving away from us

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:00.150
due to the expansion
of the universe.

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:03.790
And so I have a little
simulation here to show you.

00:06:03.790 --> 00:06:06.330
I got a bunch of
galaxies on a slide here,

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:08.520
and through the
miracle of PowerPoint,

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:10.860
I just blew up the space.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:13.290
And so the galaxies
are then further apart,

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:14.850
and I did it again.

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:16.770
And then let's look
at what this looks

00:06:16.770 --> 00:06:19.020
like from the point of
view of our galaxy, which

00:06:19.020 --> 00:06:21.100
is at the center of the
universe, of course.

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:22.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:22.350 --> 00:06:26.040
And so it looks to us
like other galaxies

00:06:26.040 --> 00:06:27.940
are moving away from us.

00:06:27.940 --> 00:06:30.960
And the ones that
are farthest from us,

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:34.230
cover more distance in a
certain amount of time, which

00:06:34.230 --> 00:06:35.790
means they're moving faster.

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:37.440
So it explains Hubble's law.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:39.180
And I'm sure both
Chris and Father

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:41.992
Guy explained that
actually, we are

00:06:41.992 --> 00:06:43.950
at the center of the
universe, but everybody is

00:06:43.950 --> 00:06:45.460
at the center of the universe.

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:48.930
So if we picked any other
galaxy, say that one,

00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:55.360
and just looked at what it saw,
it sees exactly the same thing.

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:59.490
So this expansion of space,
everybody sees the universe.

00:06:59.490 --> 00:07:02.280
Everybody sees all the other
galaxies moving away from it

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:04.740
and thinks that it's at
the center of the universe.

00:07:04.740 --> 00:07:07.710
And actually, that's
a Harvard phenomenon,

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:10.362
but it really does
work in the universe.

00:07:10.362 --> 00:07:11.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:16.170
And so this expansion
of space, the universe

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:17.760
is just scaling up.

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:21.240
And then the discovery of the
cosmic microwave background

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:25.400
by Penzias and Wilson
in 1964 told us-- well,

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:28.440
I should have said that the
implications of Hubble's

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:31.740
discovery was, in the beginning,
the universe was small,

00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:33.430
and it got bigger and evolved.

00:07:33.430 --> 00:07:36.510
And so there was a big bang.

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:39.330
Penzias and Wilson
discovered that there

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:43.650
are billions of
microwave photons filling

00:07:43.650 --> 00:07:47.250
the universe for every atom
and that this is the heat

00:07:47.250 --> 00:07:49.140
leftover from the Big Bang.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:51.930
And that the Big Bang
was a hot Big Bang.

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:54.610
And that changes everything,
because in the beginning,

00:07:54.610 --> 00:07:56.339
it was really hot.

00:07:56.339 --> 00:07:58.130
And I'm going to use
a technical term here.

00:07:58.130 --> 00:07:59.874
It was hotter than hell.

00:07:59.874 --> 00:08:01.724
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:01.724 --> 00:08:04.140
I think I'm allowed to do that
because Father Guy probably

00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:05.594
said the same thing.

00:08:05.594 --> 00:08:06.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:09.210
And you know, when
you heat something up,

00:08:09.210 --> 00:08:12.120
you reduce it to
its basic elements.

00:08:12.120 --> 00:08:14.160
And so that means that
in the beginning--

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:14.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:17.730
--The universe was
a primordial soup.

00:08:17.730 --> 00:08:23.100
So this is 1964, Penzias
and Wilson, hot Big Bang.

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:26.140
And so what is
primordial soup made of?

00:08:26.140 --> 00:08:29.680
And so in the 1970s,
we figured out

00:08:29.680 --> 00:08:34.480
what the basic pieces, what the
basic building blocks of matter

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:35.260
are.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:37.360
And those are called quarks.

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:40.059
And that was done
with experiments

00:08:40.059 --> 00:08:43.530
at this linear accelerator
in Chicago, Illinois.

00:08:43.530 --> 00:08:44.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:47.310
The two-mile long
Stanford Linear-- or I

00:08:47.310 --> 00:08:48.690
guess it's in California.

00:08:48.690 --> 00:08:50.562
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:51.970 --> 00:08:54.160
Well, you know why Chicago
is called the Windy City,

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:55.370
don't you?

00:08:55.370 --> 00:08:57.556
It has nothing to
do with weather.

00:08:57.556 --> 00:08:58.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:01.960
So it was experiments done at
the Stanford Linear Accelerator

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:05.650
that showed the following,
that-- so everybody knows

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:06.490
about atoms.

00:09:06.490 --> 00:09:09.310
And they have a nucleus made
of neutrons and protons.

00:09:09.310 --> 00:09:12.460
And these experiments showed
that the neutrons and protons

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:15.730
were made of smaller
entities called quarks.

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:20.440
And so by knowing that and
combining that with the fact

00:09:20.440 --> 00:09:23.860
that the universe was
hot in the beginning,

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:26.100
we can figure out what
that primordial soup was.

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:28.240
So I'm going to show
you a full-scale model

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:33.400
of the entire universe
that we can see today,

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:37.402
what it would have looked
like at the beginning.

00:09:37.402 --> 00:09:39.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.410
And this is done to scale.

00:09:41.410 --> 00:09:43.930
I didn't say it's
the entire universe.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:46.000
It's everything
we can see, which

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.980
is 100-- I think Chris
Impey told you-- there's

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:51.640
100 billion galaxies all
fit in this soup can.

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:57.000
And they were reduced to
their core constituents.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:58.520
OK.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:09:59.990
So this is what we know.

00:09:59.990 --> 00:10:03.410
We can now reconstruct the
history of the universe

00:10:03.410 --> 00:10:06.260
from quark soup to us.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:11.240
And this reconstruction took
about 13.7 billion years,

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:13.340
so I'm not just going
to step you through it.

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:15.030
I'll speed it up
just a little bit.

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:16.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:20.960
So when the universe was younger
than one 100,000th of a second,

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:22.490
it was this quark soup.

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:26.870
And as we follow it through,
it's expanding, it's cooling,

00:10:26.870 --> 00:10:30.230
layer upon layer of
structure is building up.

00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:35.090
And so when it was about one
100,000th of a second old,

00:10:35.090 --> 00:10:38.070
it was cool enough for
neutrons and protons to form.

00:10:38.070 --> 00:10:40.550
Now, I know all of you
took science classes,

00:10:40.550 --> 00:10:42.260
and you all know
that protons are blue

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:43.810
and neutrons are green.

00:10:43.810 --> 00:10:46.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:46.890 --> 00:10:51.090
And as it cooled, it became
cool enough for the neutrons

00:10:51.090 --> 00:10:55.334
and protons to come together and
make the nuclei of the lightest

00:10:55.334 --> 00:10:57.000
elements in the
periodic table, and that

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.520
happened when the universe
was a few seconds old.

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:01.200
When the universe was
a few seconds old,

00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:03.420
it was a nuclear reactor.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:06.450
And that nuclear reactor
made a lot of helium.

00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:09.390
It made a little
bit of deuterium.

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:12.780
It made some helium three, so
that's a light form of helium,

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:15.990
and it made a tiny
amount of lithium.

00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:19.020
The rest of the elements
in the periodic table

00:11:19.020 --> 00:11:20.610
were made in stars.

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:22.950
And I believe it's next week
that Phil Pinto is going

00:11:22.950 --> 00:11:27.070
to tell you about how stars made
the rest of the periodic table.

00:11:27.070 --> 00:11:32.490
Now, I know that intelligent
design is a hot issue.

00:11:32.490 --> 00:11:33.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.874
And I want to use
you as a focus group

00:11:35.874 --> 00:11:37.290
here and give you
my best argument

00:11:37.290 --> 00:11:39.390
against intelligent design.

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:41.490
My best argument against
intelligent design

00:11:41.490 --> 00:11:46.480
was the tiny amount of lithium
that was made in the Big Bang.

00:11:46.480 --> 00:11:48.550
If it was really
intelligent design,

00:11:48.550 --> 00:11:50.050
the creator would
have known that we

00:11:50.050 --> 00:11:52.341
needed much more lithium to
deal with our mental health

00:11:52.341 --> 00:11:53.401
problems.

00:11:53.401 --> 00:11:54.754
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:54.754 --> 00:11:56.107
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:56.841 --> 00:11:57.340
OK.

00:11:57.340 --> 00:11:59.576
Well, the focus group
likes that argument.

00:11:59.576 --> 00:12:00.940
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:01.720
OK.

00:12:01.720 --> 00:12:03.610
So we now have nuclei.

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:05.770
Universe is cooling
and expanding.

00:12:05.770 --> 00:12:09.040
And when it's about
400,000 years old,

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:12.490
it's cool enough for the
nuclei to capture electrons.

00:12:12.490 --> 00:12:15.280
And now we have atoms.

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:19.150
And once the atoms form-- this
is a very interesting time

00:12:19.150 --> 00:12:22.840
that we'll come back
to-- once the atoms form,

00:12:22.840 --> 00:12:25.660
the light in the universe,
the radiation in the universe,

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:27.380
travels long distances.

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:29.836
And so this is the farthest
point that we can see back to.

00:12:29.836 --> 00:12:31.210
And I'll come back
to that again,

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:33.160
and I bet Chris
talked about that.

00:12:33.160 --> 00:12:35.530
And then gravity took over.

00:12:35.530 --> 00:12:36.970
Gravity is the master builder.

00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:38.740
We'll talk more about that.

00:12:38.740 --> 00:12:42.490
And stars, and galaxies, and
so on and so forth were made.

00:12:42.490 --> 00:12:46.060
And so we can reconstruct
the history of the universe

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:48.580
from this early
time until today.

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.400
And along the way,
we have tests.

00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:55.450
So this is not
just a nice story.

00:12:55.450 --> 00:12:59.350
This is a story that's
supported by scientific fact.

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:02.650
So we predict how much
helium, deuterium, lithium,

00:13:02.650 --> 00:13:04.930
and helium three
is made back there,

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:09.319
and ask if the most primitive
samples of universe-- that

00:13:09.319 --> 00:13:11.860
is, samples of the universe that
haven't been through stars--

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:13.300
have that amount.

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:17.200
And so we can test this theory
all the way back to about 10

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:19.490
to the minus five seconds.

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:20.260
OK.

00:13:20.260 --> 00:13:25.570
So let me talk about some of
the measurements that we make

00:13:25.570 --> 00:13:28.090
with the instruments
that we have today

00:13:28.090 --> 00:13:33.520
that explore this vast universe,
vast both in space and in time.

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:36.070
So the universe, the part
of the universe, we can see,

00:13:36.070 --> 00:13:38.650
is about 13 billion
light years across,

00:13:38.650 --> 00:13:42.020
and the universe is about
13 billion years old.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:46.480
These are numbers that are very
hard to get your head around.

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:47.980
But we now have
instruments that can

00:13:47.980 --> 00:13:50.710
take us all the way to the
edge of the visible universe

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:51.565
and back in time.

00:13:51.565 --> 00:13:53.487
So let me show you some
of those instruments.

00:13:53.487 --> 00:13:55.570
Now, this slide I probably
don't need to show you.

00:13:55.570 --> 00:13:58.450
And probably, I'm in a little
bit of trouble for showing you,

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:01.540
because I think you all know
about big optical telescopes.

00:14:01.540 --> 00:14:05.324
And unfortunately, I don't have
any Arizona telescopes here.

00:14:05.324 --> 00:14:07.584
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:12.006
OK.

00:14:12.006 --> 00:14:13.380
Well, actually,
let me talk about

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:15.030
these European
telescopes, because I

00:14:15.030 --> 00:14:16.500
can tell another joke here so--

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:18.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:22.500
The Europeans have their
telescopes in Chile.

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:25.980
These are four 8.2
meter telescopes.

00:14:25.980 --> 00:14:29.100
You need a special camera
to be able to photograph

00:14:29.100 --> 00:14:30.780
all of these telescopes
when standing

00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:32.310
on top of the mountain.

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:35.100
And they had a recent
distinguished visitor

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:40.470
who visited Paranal, is
their observatory in Chile.

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:41.070
I visited it.

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:43.260
It's a really spectacular place.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:46.740
And this visitor
said, you know, this

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:49.310
is the way God would have
done it if he had the money.

00:14:49.310 --> 00:14:51.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:51.540 --> 00:14:53.640
So this is really--
well, in Chicago,

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:57.420
we use Thorstein
Veblen, who just called

00:14:57.420 --> 00:14:58.972
this conspicuous consumption.

00:14:58.972 --> 00:14:59.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:01.740
And this is the
Gemini telescope,

00:15:01.740 --> 00:15:04.440
and-- oh, actually, these
are Roger Angel mirrors.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:07.290
These are the Magellan
telescopes in Chile.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:09.330
So these are Roger
Angel mirrors.

00:15:09.330 --> 00:15:11.460
And then the two
biggest telescopes

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:13.320
in the world, the
Keck telescopes.

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:16.140
And of course, we have
telescopes in space.

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:18.660
We have our first space
telescope, the Hubble,

00:15:18.660 --> 00:15:21.007
but we also have the Chandra.

00:15:21.007 --> 00:15:23.340
Oh, let's see, Chandra was
at the University of Chicago.

00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:25.200
Hubble was at the
University of Chicago.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:25.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:28.440
And then we have the Fermi
Gamma Ray Observatory.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:30.600
Oh, Fermi was at the
University of Chicago.

00:15:30.600 --> 00:15:31.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:32.949
And then we have the Spitzer.

00:15:32.949 --> 00:15:35.364
Well, Spitzer must have been
at the University of Chicago.

00:15:35.364 --> 00:15:36.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:36.090 --> 00:15:39.061
Well, he never taught there, but
he did go through O'Hare once.

00:15:39.061 --> 00:15:41.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:41.890 --> 00:15:44.290
And then I think all
of you are aware,

00:15:44.290 --> 00:15:46.570
everybody here in
the audience probably

00:15:46.570 --> 00:15:49.480
has a digital camera in
their pocket or their purse.

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:54.730
And these cameras that use
charged-coupled devices

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:57.050
are extraordinary
for two reasons.

00:15:57.050 --> 00:16:00.100
Number one, the old photographic
plates that Hubble used only

00:16:00.100 --> 00:16:03.730
collected about 1% of the light.

00:16:03.730 --> 00:16:09.160
These CCD's collect
almost 100% of the light.

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:11.920
And you can digitize
the picture.

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:12.790
You can distort it.

00:16:12.790 --> 00:16:15.950
You can make it look
like anything you want.

00:16:15.950 --> 00:16:18.100
You can put it on the web.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:20.560
Actually, you can do really
good scientific stuff with it.

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:25.000
And the cameras that we have
now, 100 megapixel are common,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.880
and the biggest ones
are a billion pixels.

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:30.430
And this has changed
the way astronomy

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:32.380
is done for the better.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:35.740
So I want to show you the
most famous picture in all

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:38.680
of astronomy, and I also
want to congratulate you

00:16:38.680 --> 00:16:40.810
on your good taste.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:42.670
So this is called the
Hubble Deep Field,

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:44.710
or the Hubble point and shoot.

00:16:44.710 --> 00:16:46.480
How many people have seen this?

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:49.030
I should ask, how many
people haven't seen this?

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:53.000
So this image of the
universe cost you $2 billion.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:56.350
And it was worth every penny.

00:16:56.350 --> 00:16:57.970
It was a bargain.

00:16:57.970 --> 00:17:00.400
So this answers the
age-old question,

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:02.980
how far can you
see on a clear day?

00:17:02.980 --> 00:17:03.710
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:03.710 --> 00:17:06.130
So this is as far
as you can see,

00:17:06.130 --> 00:17:09.460
and the reason that you can't
see any farther than this

00:17:09.460 --> 00:17:12.460
is you're looking
out so far in space

00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:13.960
that you're looking
back to the time

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:16.510
when galaxies were being born.

00:17:16.510 --> 00:17:18.579
And if you looked out
any farther in space,

00:17:18.579 --> 00:17:21.190
there weren't galaxies to see.

00:17:21.190 --> 00:17:25.210
So this truly answers, how far
can you see on a clear day.

00:17:25.210 --> 00:17:28.540
Just let me wax poetic a
little more about this.

00:17:28.540 --> 00:17:31.120
This is about 1/10
millionth of the sky.

00:17:31.120 --> 00:17:33.280
A tiny, tiny little
bit of the sky.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:38.120
It's such a small part of the
sky that there's only one star.

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:40.000
Or let's see, is there two?

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:41.020
Depends how you crop it.

00:17:41.020 --> 00:17:41.530
There's one.

00:17:41.530 --> 00:17:42.850
I think there's only one.

00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:47.140
The rest of the images in this,
all these other little funny

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:50.032
looking images, are galaxies.

00:17:50.032 --> 00:17:51.740
There are several
thousand galaxies here.

00:17:51.740 --> 00:17:53.830
If you multiply
that by 10 million,

00:17:53.830 --> 00:17:56.290
you get the 100 billion number.

00:17:56.290 --> 00:17:58.810
100 billion galaxies
in the universe.

00:17:58.810 --> 00:18:02.830
And you'll notice that some
of these galaxies look funny,

00:18:02.830 --> 00:18:05.800
and it's not that you
bought a crummy telescope.

00:18:05.800 --> 00:18:09.430
It's that you're looking back
to galaxies being formed,

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:12.910
and so they don't look
like galaxies today.

00:18:12.910 --> 00:18:14.260
So this is what the Hubble did.

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:19.390
This is one of
the-- you know, I'm

00:18:19.390 --> 00:18:22.600
going to ask you to look at this
kind of like a Monet painting.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:25.840
So don't get scared
away by the graphs here.

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:30.190
We can now construct-- we
live in an evolving universe.

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:33.700
There weren't always stars, and
there won't always be stars.

00:18:33.700 --> 00:18:36.070
And so what we've been
able to reconstruct

00:18:36.070 --> 00:18:39.740
is the star formation
history of the universe.

00:18:39.740 --> 00:18:41.260
So this is time.

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.530
And don't worry about
these funny numbers here.

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:47.650
So this is the Big Bang
back here, and this is now.

00:18:47.650 --> 00:18:52.390
So time moves from-- so think of
this as an Old Testament Bible.

00:18:52.390 --> 00:18:54.760
You have to read it
from right to left.

00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:56.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:59.310
And this is the rate at
which stars were forming.

00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:01.590
So start out really slow.

00:19:01.590 --> 00:19:06.330
And stars were really forming
a lot when the universe was

00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:07.650
a couple billion years old.

00:19:07.650 --> 00:19:09.870
This is the time up here.

00:19:09.870 --> 00:19:12.990
And today, there's
hardly any stars forming.

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:16.070
We're just about
done forming stars.

00:19:16.070 --> 00:19:19.490
And so this is the
star formation history

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:20.350
of the universe.

00:19:22.870 --> 00:19:26.170
And then the Hubble diagram.

00:19:26.170 --> 00:19:29.500
So we all laugh
at Hubble's data,

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:31.720
but he was the one
who showed us that we

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:33.410
live in an evolving universe.

00:19:33.410 --> 00:19:36.770
So this is the best Hubble
diagram that we have.

00:19:36.770 --> 00:19:39.640
And so, this again,
is the velocity

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:42.979
of galaxies moving away from
us versus their distance.

00:19:42.979 --> 00:19:44.770
And now it actually
looks like these points

00:19:44.770 --> 00:19:46.840
lie on a straight line.

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:48.970
And let me show
you Hubble's data.

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:53.290
So all of Hubble's data would
fit in this tiny little part

00:19:53.290 --> 00:19:54.110
of the graph.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:55.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:55.850 --> 00:19:59.150
And here is the data
that he would have added.

00:19:59.150 --> 00:20:01.160
And you know, his
data wasn't so good,

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:03.200
and I won't tell you
what value he got.

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.540
The correct value is about 70.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:08.450
The value Hubble got was 550.

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:10.490
So this expansion
rate of the universe

00:20:10.490 --> 00:20:14.010
is extremely important,
because the expansion rate

00:20:14.010 --> 00:20:17.880
of the universe tells us how
long back to the Big Bang,

00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:22.650
among other things, and
how big the universe is.

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:24.480
This also tells
us that girls are

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:26.040
better astronomers than boys.

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:28.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:28.480 --> 00:20:31.581
And this is why we tried to
keep them out of astronomy.

00:20:31.581 --> 00:20:33.545
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:34.530 --> 00:20:36.348
We're not stupid.

00:20:36.348 --> 00:20:38.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:38.070 --> 00:20:40.440
So the team that measured
the Hubble constant

00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:41.836
was led by Wendy Freedman.

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:49.540
Now, let's talk about how far
you can see with microwaves.

00:20:49.540 --> 00:20:52.290
And so this is the cosmic
microwave background,

00:20:52.290 --> 00:20:56.550
and this was a very
important discovery in 1992.

00:20:56.550 --> 00:20:58.710
NASA sent up a satellite
called, its friends

00:20:58.710 --> 00:21:02.430
called it COBE, cosmic
background explorer,

00:21:02.430 --> 00:21:05.130
to carefully measure the
radiation from the microwave

00:21:05.130 --> 00:21:06.120
background.

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:10.230
And for the technical
buffs here, it

00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:12.930
measured the spectrum of
the microwave background

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:16.050
and found it to be almost
a perfect black body

00:21:16.050 --> 00:21:21.540
with a temperature
of 2.7255 5 kelvin.

00:21:21.540 --> 00:21:23.400
But what I really wanted
to talk about here

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:26.400
is this is how the intensity
of the microwave background

00:21:26.400 --> 00:21:28.570
varies across the sky.

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:30.510
So this is the
whole sky projected

00:21:30.510 --> 00:21:33.360
on a piece of graph paper,
like when you went to school,

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.610
they projected the whole
Earth on an ellipse.

00:21:35.610 --> 00:21:37.450
So that's the whole sky.

00:21:37.450 --> 00:21:40.170
And this is one of
these color diagrams.

00:21:40.170 --> 00:21:43.556
And so you might say, well,
this is really boring.

00:21:43.556 --> 00:21:45.930
Well, it is boring because
the intensity of the microwave

00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:49.990
background is essentially
the same in all directions.

00:21:49.990 --> 00:21:53.220
If you look at it
very, very carefully,

00:21:53.220 --> 00:21:57.450
it's slightly more intense
or hotter in one direction.

00:21:57.450 --> 00:22:02.020
This is towards the
constellation Leo.

00:22:02.020 --> 00:22:03.620
Yeah, I wish I could
stop that, but I

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:04.885
don't know how to stop that.

00:22:04.885 --> 00:22:05.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:08.160
And it's cooler in
the other direction.

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:10.250
This is called the
giant dipole in the sky.

00:22:10.250 --> 00:22:12.960
Two poles, one
here and one there.

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:16.910
And it tells us that with
respect to the cosmic rest

00:22:16.910 --> 00:22:18.530
frame of the
universe, we're moving

00:22:18.530 --> 00:22:22.250
at 620 kilometers per second.

00:22:22.250 --> 00:22:24.650
And that's interesting.

00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:26.450
But what was most
interesting, and what

00:22:26.450 --> 00:22:33.020
resulted in the Nobel Prize
for Mather and Smoot was this.

00:22:33.020 --> 00:22:35.300
So if you take away
the dipole, there

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:38.780
are tiny fluctuations
in the intensity,

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:41.990
about a part in a 100,000--
or if you want it in kelvin,

00:22:41.990 --> 00:22:46.340
about 18 micro kelvin-- that
were discovered by COBE.

00:22:46.340 --> 00:22:48.420
And I'm going to tell you
how important they are.

00:22:48.420 --> 00:22:51.630
This is not the belt
of the universe.

00:22:51.630 --> 00:22:54.800
So this is microwave
emission from our own galaxy.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:56.570
So you want to ignore that.

00:22:56.570 --> 00:22:57.500
That's not important.

00:22:57.500 --> 00:23:00.380
But it's these spots here
that are very, very important,

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:01.760
that we're worth a Nobel Prize.

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.130
And so let me explain why
they were worth a-- oh.

00:23:04.130 --> 00:23:06.960
First of all, testimonials.

00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:10.940
So Stephen Hawking, when this
announcement was made in 1992,

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:14.740
said, "Greatest
discovery of all time."

00:23:14.740 --> 00:23:17.890
Now, you know, the Brits are
not known for their reserve.

00:23:17.890 --> 00:23:20.950
They're way over exuberant,
and this may only

00:23:20.950 --> 00:23:22.480
be a slightly overstatement.

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:27.400
So a California boy was a
little more reserved in his--

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:29.860
"This was a very big discovery."

00:23:29.860 --> 00:23:32.110
And the reason it was
a very big discovery

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:35.890
is that this was the
evidence for the lumpiness

00:23:35.890 --> 00:23:38.500
in the distribution of
matter in the universe

00:23:38.500 --> 00:23:40.930
that seeded all the
structure that we see today.

00:23:40.930 --> 00:23:43.060
And by structure, I mean
galaxies, and clusters

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:45.730
of galaxies, and stars, and us.

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:47.540
So that's a really big deal.

00:23:47.540 --> 00:23:51.440
So let me come back and blow up
part of that earlier diagram.

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:52.720
So here we are.

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:53.930
We look out in space.

00:23:53.930 --> 00:23:55.780
We look back in time.

00:23:55.780 --> 00:23:59.950
And let's see, so here are
some of those galaxies that

00:23:59.950 --> 00:24:03.880
were seen by the
Hubble Space Telescope.

00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:05.470
So we go back to
when the universe was

00:24:05.470 --> 00:24:08.800
about a billion years old, and
then we can't see anything.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:11.710
As I told you before, that
the so-called dark ages,

00:24:11.710 --> 00:24:13.600
where nothing was lit up.

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:17.800
And the photons that come from
the greatest distance to us

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:20.530
come from this time
when the universe

00:24:20.530 --> 00:24:23.980
went from being nuclei
and electrons-- we

00:24:23.980 --> 00:24:28.030
call that ionized matter--
to be two atoms forming.

00:24:28.030 --> 00:24:31.720
And why that works, for
the technical people here,

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:35.440
is ionized matter is
very opaque to radiation.

00:24:35.440 --> 00:24:37.960
And in fact, Joaquin, did
we get that waiver thing

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:40.750
so that we could turn
the room into a plasma

00:24:40.750 --> 00:24:42.655
and then people wouldn't
be able to see me?

00:24:42.655 --> 00:24:43.030
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:43.030 --> 00:24:44.488
We didn't get-- we
didn't get that.

00:24:44.488 --> 00:24:45.210
OK.

00:24:45.210 --> 00:24:45.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:45.790 --> 00:24:46.289
Sorry.

