And so these microwave
photons go all the way back

00:24:53.350 --> 00:24:59.350
to this time before stars when
the universe was almost uniform

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:05.410
mush with small variations in
the density of the universe.

00:25:05.410 --> 00:25:11.200
So some regions were about 0.01%
more dense and other regions

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:12.520
were less dense.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:16.510
And then gravity took
the more dense regions

00:25:16.510 --> 00:25:19.510
and pulled in more material.

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:21.760
And then their
gravity got stronger,

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:23.920
and then more material fell in.

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:27.220
And so during the
next 13 billion years

00:25:27.220 --> 00:25:30.700
or so, galaxies and other
structures built up.

00:25:30.700 --> 00:25:35.080
And this model of how
structure formed by gravity

00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:38.530
is, I think, a University of
Chicago Economics Department

00:25:38.530 --> 00:25:39.340
model.

00:25:39.340 --> 00:25:42.760
So if you think about it,
where there was more matter,

00:25:42.760 --> 00:25:44.450
those regions got
even more matter.

00:25:44.450 --> 00:25:45.700
So the rich get richer.

00:25:45.700 --> 00:25:46.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:46.690 --> 00:25:49.034
And where there's
less matter, you know,

00:25:49.034 --> 00:25:51.200
they lose their matter to
where there's more matter.

00:25:51.200 --> 00:25:53.110
So the poor get poorer.

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:54.974
So this was a model
built by University

00:25:54.974 --> 00:25:55.890
of Chicago economists.

00:25:55.890 --> 00:25:56.590
[LAUGHTER]

