00:37:03.630 --> 00:37:06.830
And the answer is,
should be gravity.

00:37:06.830 --> 00:37:08.270
Gravity is the universal glue.

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:09.650
It holds things together.

00:37:09.650 --> 00:37:14.291
The planets in our solar system
move fast, not quite this fast,

00:37:14.291 --> 00:37:16.040
and it's the gravity
of the sun that holds

00:37:16.040 --> 00:37:18.820
the solar system together.

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:20.980
Except he found a
small, little problem.

00:37:20.980 --> 00:37:24.988
If you add up all the
gravity of all the--

00:37:24.988 --> 00:37:26.956
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:26.956 --> 00:37:31.476
You know, this slide was perfect
when I put it in this machine.

00:37:31.476 --> 00:37:32.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:32.730 --> 00:37:34.735
It's this cheap
equipment you have here.

00:37:34.735 --> 00:37:35.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:35.990 --> 00:37:39.340
So if you add up all the
gravity of all the stars in all

00:37:39.340 --> 00:37:42.670
the galaxies, it's not enough
to hold the cluster together.

00:37:42.670 --> 00:37:45.450
It's off by a factor of 50.

00:37:45.450 --> 00:37:49.620
And so Zwicky was
bold enough to say,

00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:52.560
clusters must be held
together by the gravity

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:55.440
of unseen material.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:57.030
Dark matter.

00:37:57.030 --> 00:38:00.450
Now, there were
alternative hypotheses,

00:38:00.450 --> 00:38:03.228
including that Fritz
Zwicky is crazy.

00:38:03.228 --> 00:38:04.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:04.920 --> 00:38:06.750
One of the
alternative hypotheses

00:38:06.750 --> 00:38:08.760
is, there aren't
really clusters.

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:12.900
That was a chance passing
of galaxies in the night.

00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:16.290
And it was-- you know,
cosmology was young.

00:38:16.290 --> 00:38:17.750
Equipment wasn't good.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:20.130
The idea didn't catch on.

00:38:20.130 --> 00:38:21.630
But we now know that's true.

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:25.110
And in fact, we can
image the dark matter.

00:38:25.110 --> 00:38:28.440
And let me show you another
wonderful Hubble image.

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:30.790
So this is a
cluster of galaxies.

00:38:30.790 --> 00:38:34.015
So the orange galaxies
are in a cluster.

00:38:34.015 --> 00:38:35.489
Oh, you can't see
the phone number.

00:38:35.489 --> 00:38:36.030
That's right.

00:38:36.030 --> 00:38:37.821
We blacked it out
because some people would

00:38:37.821 --> 00:38:40.170
try to call it on their phone.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:42.960
So this is a
cluster of galaxies.

00:38:42.960 --> 00:38:46.380
And behind this
cluster of galaxies,

00:38:46.380 --> 00:38:48.420
much farther away
in the universe,

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:52.560
are very faint galaxies
called faint blue galaxies.

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:54.490
We're really good
at naming things.

00:38:54.490 --> 00:38:54.990
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:54.990 --> 00:38:57.420
And the light from these
faint blue galaxies

00:38:57.420 --> 00:39:00.150
that I'm pointing at has
to pass through the cluster

00:39:00.150 --> 00:39:01.320
to get to us.

00:39:01.320 --> 00:39:03.690
Now, one of the predictions
of Einstein's theory

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:06.330
is that gravity bends light.

00:39:06.330 --> 00:39:09.720
And anything that bends
light we just call a lens.

00:39:09.720 --> 00:39:12.450
So gravity acts like a lens.

00:39:12.450 --> 00:39:16.360
And what it does is
produce multiple images.

00:39:16.360 --> 00:39:18.750
So all of these
ring-like galaxies,

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:21.580
that's not a bunch of
galaxies that are twins.

00:39:21.580 --> 00:39:24.480
That's multiple images
of the same galaxy.

00:39:24.480 --> 00:39:30.450
And galaxy-- actually,
a gravitational lens

00:39:30.450 --> 00:39:33.270
is not a great lens.

00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:34.860
It distorts.

00:39:34.860 --> 00:39:35.880
It shears.

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:40.950
It stretches the image of
the galaxies behind it.

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:44.250
But that's a really good thing
because we know how it does it.

00:39:44.250 --> 00:39:47.130
And by looking at the
pattern of multiple images

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:50.490
and distortions, you can
reconstruct the distribution

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:55.260
of mass in that cluster, and
that's what the next slide is.

00:39:55.260 --> 00:40:01.090
So these are the two coordinates
on the sky that you just saw,

00:40:01.090 --> 00:40:03.060
so this coordinate
and that coordinate.

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:07.290
And the up coordinate is how
much mass at a given position.

00:40:07.290 --> 00:40:09.870
And so these spiky
little things tell you

00:40:09.870 --> 00:40:11.730
how good this technique is.

00:40:11.730 --> 00:40:13.920
These are the
individual galaxies

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:16.320
that you saw in
that previous image.

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:18.830
And you might say, well,
where's the dark matter?

00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:21.760
Well, the dark matter
isn't quite so conspicuous,

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:24.730
but it's this
smooth distribution

00:40:24.730 --> 00:40:26.390
that goes on forever.

00:40:26.390 --> 00:40:29.800
So your eye is attracted
to these little spikes,

00:40:29.800 --> 00:40:32.380
but there's much more matter
in this smooth distribution.

00:40:32.380 --> 00:40:35.550
So we can actually image it.

00:40:35.550 --> 00:40:36.690
OK.

00:40:36.690 --> 00:40:39.120
In the 1970s-- again,
these damn girl

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:43.860
astronomers-- Vera Rubin
really convinced people

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:46.320
that this was an important
problem because she

00:40:46.320 --> 00:40:51.690
showed that without dark matter,
galaxies would fly apart.

00:40:51.690 --> 00:40:53.910
So this is the Andromeda galaxy.

00:40:53.910 --> 00:40:57.120
And in a galaxy, stars
orbit around the center

00:40:57.120 --> 00:40:58.710
of the galaxy.

00:40:58.710 --> 00:41:01.830
And so she carefully
measured the speeds

00:41:01.830 --> 00:41:05.730
of the different
stars, stars close in,

00:41:05.730 --> 00:41:09.090
stars farther away,
farther away, farther away.

00:41:09.090 --> 00:41:11.920
And the name of the
name of her result

00:41:11.920 --> 00:41:14.880
is she found flat
rotation curves.

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:19.890
And so what this meant was
there was a lot more to a galaxy

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:21.600
than that that meets
the eye, and let

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:24.510
me try to talk my
way through this.

00:41:24.510 --> 00:41:26.370
So if all of the
mass of a galaxy

00:41:26.370 --> 00:41:28.230
were associated
with the stars, it

00:41:28.230 --> 00:41:30.990
would be a bit
puzzling that when

00:41:30.990 --> 00:41:33.720
you get to the rare star
or gas cloud way out here,

00:41:33.720 --> 00:41:35.550
it's moving just as fast.

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:39.750
Because you know, gravity falls
off like 1 over R-squared.

00:41:39.750 --> 00:41:45.270
So what's holding this-- how
can these stars out here be

00:41:45.270 --> 00:41:47.130
moving as fast as those stars?

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:49.380
And so what you can't
see with the telescope

00:41:49.380 --> 00:41:54.270
is the enormous
halo of dark matter.

00:41:54.270 --> 00:41:55.240
OK.

00:41:55.240 --> 00:41:58.180
So let me talk about what
the dark matter is, and I

00:41:58.180 --> 00:42:00.650
alluded to this earlier.

00:42:00.650 --> 00:42:05.020
The amount of matter in
the universe, the 27%,

00:42:05.020 --> 00:42:08.080
and the amount of atoms
in the universe, the 4.5%,

00:42:08.080 --> 00:42:10.250
those numbers aren't equal.

00:42:10.250 --> 00:42:13.210
And to show you how
unequal they are--

00:42:13.210 --> 00:42:17.860
so this is not 4.5% but
it's a different measure

00:42:17.860 --> 00:42:18.850
of the amount of atoms.

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:21.550
So here's the amount
of atoms on a ruler.

00:42:21.550 --> 00:42:23.650
It's 21 plus or minus 1.

00:42:23.650 --> 00:42:28.210
The total amount of matter
is a 130 plus or minus 5.

00:42:28.210 --> 00:42:31.640
And so those numbers are
just wildly different.

00:42:31.640 --> 00:42:34.660
So the dark matter
can't be atoms.

00:42:34.660 --> 00:42:37.060
It has to be a new
form of matter.

00:42:37.060 --> 00:42:39.880
And you know, Carl
Sagan reminded us

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:41.420
that we're made
out of star stuff,

00:42:41.420 --> 00:42:43.501
and we thought that
was really cool.

00:42:43.501 --> 00:42:45.250
But now I'm going to
tell you the universe

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:46.630
isn't made out of star stuff.

00:42:46.630 --> 00:42:48.500
It's made out of
this dark matter.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:51.210
So what is it?

00:42:51.210 --> 00:42:51.710
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:51.710 --> 00:42:55.620
So we don't know what it is.

00:42:55.620 --> 00:43:00.150
It's hard for a theorist
to say that, you know?

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:03.870
But here is our best hypothesis.

00:43:03.870 --> 00:43:06.750
In fact, this is our most
conservative hypothesis.

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:09.180
I'm not saying it's right,
but this is the corner

00:43:09.180 --> 00:43:11.090
we've worked ourselves into.

00:43:11.090 --> 00:43:14.010
That the dark matter
is made of a new kind

00:43:14.010 --> 00:43:15.960
of particle of nature.

00:43:15.960 --> 00:43:20.640
And the three possibilities
when I drew this slide in 1990

00:43:20.640 --> 00:43:23.592
were a particle
called the axion,

00:43:23.592 --> 00:43:25.800
a particle called the
neutralino, which I'll tell you

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:27.870
more about, and then
everybody in the room

00:43:27.870 --> 00:43:29.730
has heard of neutrinos.

00:43:29.730 --> 00:43:32.790
And in 1990, we thought
that the dark matter just

00:43:32.790 --> 00:43:33.722
might be neutrinos.

00:43:33.722 --> 00:43:36.180
We knew how many neutrinos
there were leftover from the Big

00:43:36.180 --> 00:43:39.720
Bang, but it turns out that
their masses-- we've now

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:42.480
measured their masses
and they don't weigh

00:43:42.480 --> 00:43:43.890
enough to be the dark matter.

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:46.380
So they're a little
cosmic spice,

00:43:46.380 --> 00:43:48.120
but they're not the dark matter.

00:43:48.120 --> 00:43:50.640
So let me tell you
about the neutralino.

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:53.910
So this is a
hypothetical particle,

00:43:53.910 --> 00:43:58.290
which is a fancy word that means
it doesn't exist as far as we

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:00.750
know, but we hope it exists.

00:44:00.750 --> 00:44:03.150
This is a particle
that, if it exists,

00:44:03.150 --> 00:44:07.590
weighs 100, maybe 200, maybe
500 times what a proton does.

00:44:07.590 --> 00:44:10.470
This is a particle
whose existence

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:13.040
has been predicted by
particle physicists who

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:15.550
were working on a whole
different class of problems.

00:44:15.550 --> 00:44:18.040
Everybody's heard
of string theory?

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:19.750
Everybody's heard
of string theory.

00:44:19.750 --> 00:44:20.400
OK.

00:44:20.400 --> 00:44:21.816
Everybody's heard
of Brian Greene?

00:44:21.816 --> 00:44:22.820
Yeah.

00:44:22.820 --> 00:44:23.490
OK.

00:44:23.490 --> 00:44:27.840
So if string theory is right,
for every particle we know,

00:44:27.840 --> 00:44:29.610
there's a
super-symmetric partner.

00:44:29.610 --> 00:44:32.610
And the neutralino is the
lightest super-symmetric

00:44:32.610 --> 00:44:33.330
partner.

00:44:33.330 --> 00:44:36.930
It's a particle whose existence
traces to string theory.

00:44:36.930 --> 00:44:41.790
And so you might ask, where
are these neutralinos?

00:44:41.790 --> 00:44:45.270
Well, the answer
that Brian would give

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:47.064
is, we're about
to discover them.

00:44:47.064 --> 00:44:48.060
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:48.060 --> 00:44:49.175
And I'll tell you why.

00:44:49.175 --> 00:44:50.550
And then there's
another particle

00:44:50.550 --> 00:44:53.160
that I don't have time
to tell you about.

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:55.560
Again, it's a
hypothetical particle

00:44:55.560 --> 00:45:00.420
that solves a problem
in the subatomic world.

00:45:00.420 --> 00:45:02.310
And this particle
is called the axion,

00:45:02.310 --> 00:45:04.680
and it couldn't be more
different than the neutralino.

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:08.280
It weighs about a million,
million, million times less

00:45:08.280 --> 00:45:10.890
than the neutralino, so there'd
have to be a lot of them.

00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:13.290
What's wonderful about
these particles is,

00:45:13.290 --> 00:45:16.210
even though we don't know
whether or not they exist,

00:45:16.210 --> 00:45:18.042
their predicted
particles allow us

00:45:18.042 --> 00:45:19.500
to calculate how
many of them would

00:45:19.500 --> 00:45:21.270
be leftover from the Big Bang.

00:45:21.270 --> 00:45:22.980
And guess what the answer is?

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:24.780
Enough to be that dark matter.

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.040
So this is where we are.

00:45:26.040 --> 00:45:28.870
This is an extraordinarily
bold hypothesis.

00:45:28.870 --> 00:45:30.300
It might not be right.

00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:32.080
It's time to test it.

00:45:32.080 --> 00:45:37.480
And so I like to call this
the decade of dark matter.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:39.884
Let's see, do you have
a basketball team here?

00:45:39.884 --> 00:45:40.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:43.620
Did you guys know that
Hubble was a basketball star,

00:45:43.620 --> 00:45:47.610
and that he led the University
of Chicago to three NCAA titles

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:48.734
in a row?

00:45:48.734 --> 00:45:49.710
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:49.710 --> 00:45:51.888
Check that out,
that's a true fact.

00:45:51.888 --> 00:45:53.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:53.220 --> 00:45:56.869
So one way you can
verify the dark matter--

00:45:56.869 --> 00:45:59.160
what do I mean that we have
the full court press on it?

00:45:59.160 --> 00:46:02.730
One is that you could
produce it in an accelerator.

00:46:02.730 --> 00:46:04.590
Now, we hoped to
produce it at Fermilab,

00:46:04.590 --> 00:46:06.930
but Fermilab didn't
have enough energy.

00:46:06.930 --> 00:46:10.350
And there is a new accelerator
in Geneva, Illinois--

00:46:10.350 --> 00:46:12.244
or no, maybe it's
Geneva, Switzerland.

00:46:12.244 --> 00:46:14.034
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:14.034 --> 00:46:15.450
It's one of those
Geneva's, called

00:46:15.450 --> 00:46:17.220
the Large Hadron Collider.

00:46:17.220 --> 00:46:19.680
And if you ever visit the
Large Hadron Collider,

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:22.020
you go up on the wall
there and they say,

00:46:22.020 --> 00:46:23.940
wanted, dead or alive.

00:46:23.940 --> 00:46:26.480
The first picture is Osama bin
Laden and the second picture

00:46:26.480 --> 00:46:27.360
is the neutralino.

00:46:27.360 --> 00:46:28.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:29.250 --> 00:46:31.050
OK.

00:46:31.050 --> 00:46:36.720
If indeed the dark matter
is made out of particles,

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:39.720
then we're swimming in
dark matter in this room.

00:46:39.720 --> 00:46:44.100
So in a coffee cup, there's
about one neutralino.

00:46:44.100 --> 00:46:46.920
And so if you built a
sensitive enough detector,

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:49.110
you could detect
the neutralinos.

00:46:49.110 --> 00:46:51.270
The halo, sometimes
these neutralinos bump

00:46:51.270 --> 00:46:56.010
into each other and annihilate,
you know, destroy each other,

00:46:56.010 --> 00:46:58.635
and turn into particles
that we can detect,

00:46:58.635 --> 00:47:02.520
like photons, or
electrons, or positrons.

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:05.790
And then it could be that the
very first generations of stars

00:47:05.790 --> 00:47:07.810
were actually made
of neutralinos.

00:47:07.810 --> 00:47:10.170
So we feel like in
the next 10 years,

00:47:10.170 --> 00:47:13.350
we may finish this story of
dark matter, just in time

00:47:13.350 --> 00:47:15.480
to start the next story.

00:47:15.480 --> 00:47:18.190
So what about the dark energy?

00:47:18.190 --> 00:47:22.290
So this story starts in
1998 with the discovery

00:47:22.290 --> 00:47:25.770
that the universe is speeding
up and not slowing down.

00:47:25.770 --> 00:47:28.410
And this was on the cover
of Science Magazine.

00:47:28.410 --> 00:47:30.790
And this was called the
breakthrough discovery

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:31.620
of the year.

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:36.010
So let me remind you about
the expansion of the universe.

00:47:36.010 --> 00:47:40.740
So here's the size of
the universe versus time.

00:47:40.740 --> 00:47:43.140
And so remember that the
expansion of the universe

00:47:43.140 --> 00:47:45.460
is just the stretching of space.

00:47:45.460 --> 00:47:48.780
And so this we call the
cosmic scale factor.

00:47:48.780 --> 00:47:51.090
And so as this green
curve gets bigger,

00:47:51.090 --> 00:47:52.390
the universe is getting bigger.

00:47:52.390 --> 00:47:54.020
This is the Big Bang.

00:47:54.020 --> 00:47:59.150
And so one of the issues,
going back to Hubble,

00:47:59.150 --> 00:48:03.260
is how much is the
universe slowing down?

00:48:03.260 --> 00:48:05.690
Because gravity is
attractive, right?

00:48:05.690 --> 00:48:08.560
And so your mother,
you all saw this.

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:10.940
Your mother showed you
this curve on your knee,

00:48:10.940 --> 00:48:13.930
on her knee, or maybe your knee.

00:48:13.930 --> 00:48:15.460
I don't know how that works.

00:48:15.460 --> 00:48:17.950
But you first heard about
this story from your mother.

00:48:17.950 --> 00:48:19.750
She said, the
universe is expanding.

00:48:19.750 --> 00:48:23.660
It's slowing down so that
these curves are droopy,

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:25.782
so they're getting
slower and slower.

00:48:25.782 --> 00:48:27.740
And if there's a lot of
matter in the universe,

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:32.470
the universe will halt expanding
and then fall back on itself.

00:48:32.470 --> 00:48:34.660
And if there's not very
much matter in the universe,

00:48:34.660 --> 00:48:36.160
the universe will
slow, and slow,

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:38.530
and then eventually
it won't slow anymore.

00:48:38.530 --> 00:48:42.220
And then there's a Goldilocks
universe that slows, and slows,

00:48:42.220 --> 00:48:43.810
and slows, and slows.

00:48:43.810 --> 00:48:46.180
And at an infinite time
after the Big Bang,

00:48:46.180 --> 00:48:48.340
it stops expanding.

00:48:48.340 --> 00:48:52.150
And so one of the big
issues in cosmology

00:48:52.150 --> 00:48:54.830
was to measure the
slowing of the universe.

00:48:54.830 --> 00:48:59.134
And this is very, very hard,
but you use the Hubble diagram.

00:48:59.134 --> 00:49:00.550
So here's the
Hubble diagram where

00:49:00.550 --> 00:49:04.357
you plot the velocity of a
galaxy versus its distance.

00:49:04.357 --> 00:49:06.940
And now this is the one time I
really want you to concentrate.

00:49:06.940 --> 00:49:09.621
There is no joke coming,
so don't worry about that.

00:49:09.621 --> 00:49:10.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:10.120 --> 00:49:12.370
So this is the Hubble diagram.

00:49:12.370 --> 00:49:16.600
And if we measured velocities
and distances of galaxies

00:49:16.600 --> 00:49:19.360
today, due to the fact that
the expansion of the universe

00:49:19.360 --> 00:49:22.950
is just space expanding,
we'd get a straight line.

00:49:22.950 --> 00:49:26.476
But we cannot
measure those today.

00:49:26.476 --> 00:49:28.100
We cannot measure
the velocities today,

00:49:28.100 --> 00:49:31.100
because when we look through a
telescope and we look at a very

00:49:31.100 --> 00:49:34.060
distant object, we're
looking back in time.

00:49:34.060 --> 00:49:36.430
And so when we look at
the most distant objects,

00:49:36.430 --> 00:49:38.650
we're not measuring
the velocity today.

00:49:38.650 --> 00:49:40.960
We're measuring the
velocity way back when.

00:49:40.960 --> 00:49:44.020
And if the universe is slowing
down, the number we measure

00:49:44.020 --> 00:49:47.080
should actually be
above the straight line.

00:49:47.080 --> 00:49:49.210
And so going back to
Hubble, astronomers

00:49:49.210 --> 00:49:52.510
have been trying to put
galaxies on this diagram,

00:49:52.510 --> 00:49:56.440
on the Hubble diagram, ones
that are way far away, to see

00:49:56.440 --> 00:49:58.330
the bending of the curve.

00:49:58.330 --> 00:50:02.320
And if the universe is slowing
down, it would curve upward.

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:05.110
And the amount it curves upward,
like if it curved like that,

00:50:05.110 --> 00:50:08.530
it's really slowing down
if just curves a little.

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:10.880
So that was the goal.

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:13.490
Now, in order to do this, you
need to accurately measure

00:50:13.490 --> 00:50:14.720
distances.

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:18.020
And to accurately measure
distances in astronomy,

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:21.367
you need an object whose
brightness you know,

00:50:21.367 --> 00:50:23.450
and then you measure its
apparent brightness here.

00:50:23.450 --> 00:50:25.880
And if it's very faint,
it's very far away.

00:50:25.880 --> 00:50:28.130
And so we call these
standard candles.

00:50:28.130 --> 00:50:30.320
And the best standard
candle that we know of,

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:32.870
the standard candle that
really makes this work,

00:50:32.870 --> 00:50:35.450
is called a Type 1a Supernova.

00:50:35.450 --> 00:50:37.910
And it's basically
a star about 40%

00:50:37.910 --> 00:50:41.570
more massive than our
sun that just blows up.

00:50:41.570 --> 00:50:45.410
So it's a 1.4 solar
mass thermonuclear bomb.

00:50:45.410 --> 00:50:47.950
And so you can see them
across the universe.

00:50:47.950 --> 00:50:52.310
So here's a very distant galaxy,
