And we are building, for sure,
the Large Synoptic Survey

01:00:49.250 --> 01:00:52.880
Telescope, which will
be Roger Angel mirrors,

01:00:52.880 --> 01:00:54.680
but it won't be in Arizona.

01:00:54.680 --> 01:00:56.670
But that's not my fault.

01:00:56.670 --> 01:00:59.150
OK.

01:00:59.150 --> 01:01:02.330
Right, let me go on and
talk about inflation

01:01:02.330 --> 01:01:04.310
and then finish up
with the multiverse.

01:01:04.310 --> 01:01:10.620
So there was an idea
in the 1980s that

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:13.130
has been probably the
most influential idea

01:01:13.130 --> 01:01:17.450
since the idea of the Big Bang,
and it's called inflation.

01:01:17.450 --> 01:01:20.015
And what it really is is
this brown sentence here.

01:01:20.015 --> 01:01:23.360
"A a very short period
of rapid expansion

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:26.060
driven by vacuum energy."

01:01:26.060 --> 01:01:28.970
And in the 1980s, we were
afraid to call this accelerated

01:01:28.970 --> 01:01:31.910
expansion because the idea
was so crazy that if we added

01:01:31.910 --> 01:01:34.370
accelerated expansion,
which is what it really is,

01:01:34.370 --> 01:01:36.630
nobody would have
listened to us.

01:01:36.630 --> 01:01:38.720
So how rapid?

01:01:38.720 --> 01:01:41.610
In 10 to the -32
seconds-- for those of you

01:01:41.610 --> 01:01:44.236
who don't know what that
is, we just call it a jiffy.

01:01:44.236 --> 01:01:46.589
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:46.589 --> 01:01:47.130
I don't know.

01:01:47.130 --> 01:01:48.840
I don't know powers
of 10 either.

01:01:48.840 --> 01:01:53.370
So in a jiffy, the universe
expanded by a larger factor

01:01:53.370 --> 01:01:56.760
than it did in the
next 15 billion years.

01:01:56.760 --> 01:02:00.960
And our observable universe
began from an incredibly tiny

01:02:00.960 --> 01:02:03.780
piece of the original universe.

01:02:03.780 --> 01:02:07.490
And that explains
why it's so smooth,

01:02:07.490 --> 01:02:10.470
and also explains where
the lumps come from.

01:02:10.470 --> 01:02:12.300
So let me just run
you through that idea.

01:02:12.300 --> 01:02:16.350
So here is the
universe, very early on.

01:02:16.350 --> 01:02:19.320
One of the big puzzles is why
is our universe so smooth?

01:02:19.320 --> 01:02:21.510
Why did the microwave
background look so smooth?

01:02:21.510 --> 01:02:23.970
So a tiny, little
bit of the universe

01:02:23.970 --> 01:02:26.820
blows up due to
this vacuum energy.

01:02:26.820 --> 01:02:30.430
And for those of you who
know a little more physics,

01:02:30.430 --> 01:02:32.970
you can look at this
picture up there.

01:02:32.970 --> 01:02:34.597
[LAUGHTER]

01:02:34.597 --> 01:02:36.430
Not that I understand
that picture up there,

01:02:36.430 --> 01:02:39.520
but so this tiny, little
bit of the universe

01:02:39.520 --> 01:02:44.290
blows up, creating a big,
smooth region of the universe.

01:02:44.290 --> 01:02:46.300
And because it was
so tiny, it was flat.

01:02:46.300 --> 01:02:49.360
So creating a big, smooth
uncurved universe--

01:02:49.360 --> 01:02:53.080
oh, that's what we have--
that all that we see today

01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:54.610
can fit in.

01:02:54.610 --> 01:02:58.130
And this is the
most amazing thing,

01:02:58.130 --> 01:02:59.780
and this is why
Stephen Hawking called

01:02:59.780 --> 01:03:03.350
the discovery by COBE the
greatest discovery of all time,

01:03:03.350 --> 01:03:07.290
is that this explains where the
seeds for structure come from.

01:03:07.290 --> 01:03:12.200
So everyone knows that
at the subatomic world,

01:03:12.200 --> 01:03:14.300
things are bouncing around.

01:03:14.300 --> 01:03:16.070
Things can't be smooth.

01:03:16.070 --> 01:03:18.410
We call them fluctuations.

01:03:18.410 --> 01:03:21.964
And so in the subatomic world,
you have these fluctuations.

01:03:21.964 --> 01:03:24.380
And so you might say, oh, well,
that would be really good.

01:03:24.380 --> 01:03:27.080
So higher density here,
lower density there.

01:03:27.080 --> 01:03:29.960
But the size of these is less
than the size of an atom.

01:03:29.960 --> 01:03:32.640
So how could you make a galaxy?

01:03:32.640 --> 01:03:34.770
This tremendous
expansion of the universe

01:03:34.770 --> 01:03:40.137
stretches the fluctuations.

01:03:40.137 --> 01:03:41.220
Well, let me go back here.

01:03:41.220 --> 01:03:44.280
Just like it blows up this
piece and makes it really big,

01:03:44.280 --> 01:03:47.260
it stretches the size
of these fluctuations.

01:03:47.260 --> 01:03:51.300
So that instead of being
less than the size of an atom

01:03:51.300 --> 01:03:54.270
across, they're millions
of light years across.

01:03:54.270 --> 01:03:56.880
And so you get more matter
here and less matter there.

01:03:56.880 --> 01:03:59.160
And so that makes the
lumpiness in the universe.

01:03:59.160 --> 01:04:03.580
And if that's correct, this--
what you see on the microwave

01:04:03.580 --> 01:04:06.310
sky-- is quantum noise.

01:04:06.310 --> 01:04:10.450
And the biggest thing-- it
got blown up by inflation.

01:04:10.450 --> 01:04:12.550
And the biggest things
in the universe,

01:04:12.550 --> 01:04:17.740
galaxies, clusters of galaxies,
are made from subatomic quantum

01:04:17.740 --> 01:04:19.795
fluctuations.

01:04:19.795 --> 01:04:21.420
Now, usually at this
point in the talk,

01:04:21.420 --> 01:04:24.840
I look for the men in white
coats to be pulling me off.

01:04:24.840 --> 01:04:26.682
So that's an amazing idea.

01:04:26.682 --> 01:04:28.140
Since that didn't
happen, I'll show

01:04:28.140 --> 01:04:29.580
you one more slide about this.

01:04:29.580 --> 01:04:32.010
So this means when you
look at the microwave

01:04:32.010 --> 01:04:35.670
sky-- this is from
WMAP-- you are looking

01:04:35.670 --> 01:04:38.600
at the world's largest IMAX.

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:41.150
So you are looking
at the quantum

01:04:41.150 --> 01:04:44.060
world projected across the sky.

01:04:44.060 --> 01:04:48.590
And what you see across 10
or 20 degrees of the sky

01:04:48.590 --> 01:04:51.920
started out, at a
length scale, smaller

01:04:51.920 --> 01:04:56.150
than a billionth of
the size of a proton.

01:04:56.150 --> 01:04:57.610
So that's amazing.

01:04:57.610 --> 01:05:00.479
And let's see, I don't
really have much time

01:05:00.479 --> 01:05:01.270
to talk about this.

01:05:01.270 --> 01:05:04.270
But this kind of lumpiness
plus the dark matter

01:05:04.270 --> 01:05:08.350
is called cold dark
matter scenario.

01:05:08.350 --> 01:05:11.770
And this gives us a story
of how galaxies and clusters

01:05:11.770 --> 01:05:15.460
of galaxies were formed that we
can test with these telescopes

01:05:15.460 --> 01:05:17.175
that we build with
Roger Angel mirrors.

01:05:20.590 --> 01:05:25.630
And right now, so far,
the status of this theory

01:05:25.630 --> 01:05:26.719
is really good.

01:05:26.719 --> 01:05:29.260
When I showed you those points
from the microwave background,

01:05:29.260 --> 01:05:30.940
there was a curve through them.

01:05:30.940 --> 01:05:32.710
It wasn't a curve
that I asked my son

01:05:32.710 --> 01:05:35.450
to draw to fit all the points.

01:05:35.450 --> 01:05:38.090
That's actually what
theory predicted.

01:05:38.090 --> 01:05:38.880
OK.

01:05:38.880 --> 01:05:40.380
Now I'm going to
give you the part,

01:05:40.380 --> 01:05:42.060
this is the hardest
part of the talk.

01:05:42.060 --> 01:05:44.890
This is the one that's really
going to keep you up at night.

01:05:44.890 --> 01:05:46.890
So if you're not a good
sleeper, close your eyes

01:05:46.890 --> 01:05:49.680
and put your hands
over your ears.

01:05:49.680 --> 01:05:56.530
So inflation says that what we
used to think of as the capital

01:05:56.530 --> 01:06:02.350
B, capital B Big Bang was
kind of little b little b,

01:06:02.350 --> 01:06:03.610
our Big Bang.

01:06:03.610 --> 01:06:05.620
It was the start
of our universe.

01:06:05.620 --> 01:06:08.890
Because according to
inflation, if it happened once,

01:06:08.890 --> 01:06:10.780
it happened many times.

01:06:10.780 --> 01:06:12.670
Now, you know mathematicians
and scientists,

01:06:12.670 --> 01:06:16.420
when they say many times, what
they really mean is infinity.

01:06:16.420 --> 01:06:19.420
But if they said infinity, it
would make you feel nervous.

01:06:19.420 --> 01:06:24.580
And so this leads to the idea,
the inflationary multiverse.

01:06:24.580 --> 01:06:27.160
And here is another
Monet painting,

01:06:27.160 --> 01:06:30.250
and this has to do with--
here's the river of time.

01:06:30.250 --> 01:06:32.650
And in some ways,
there was no beginning.

01:06:32.650 --> 01:06:35.080
There were an infinite
number of beginnings.

01:06:35.080 --> 01:06:39.940
And so each one of
these inflation events

01:06:39.940 --> 01:06:42.520
creates a universe,
and these universes

01:06:42.520 --> 01:06:45.260
are completely disconnected.

01:06:45.260 --> 01:06:47.280
They can't talk to one another.

01:06:47.280 --> 01:06:50.000
And so we call this
idea the multiverse.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:53.000
And they might-- if you marry
this with string theory--

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:55.010
why you would do
that, I don't know--

01:06:55.010 --> 01:06:57.020
but if you marry this
with string theory,

01:06:57.020 --> 01:07:00.170
then these different regions,
these different pieces

01:07:00.170 --> 01:07:02.490
of the universe, might
be very different.

01:07:02.490 --> 01:07:04.490
Here's our beautiful universe.

01:07:04.490 --> 01:07:07.820
Others might be empty or
have lower dimensions.

01:07:07.820 --> 01:07:11.360
And this idea is either
the most important idea

01:07:11.360 --> 01:07:17.700
since Copernicus or it's the
biggest headache of all time.

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:19.680
Why is it a headache?

01:07:19.680 --> 01:07:22.620
Because these different
pieces of the multiverse

01:07:22.620 --> 01:07:24.210
can't communicate.

01:07:24.210 --> 01:07:26.400
And if they can't communicate,
how can we test it?

01:07:26.400 --> 01:07:29.600
And if we can't test it,
how can it be science?

01:07:29.600 --> 01:07:33.440
And so that's why
this is a headache,

01:07:33.440 --> 01:07:36.144
because it's a really important
idea that might even be true.

01:07:36.144 --> 01:07:38.060
But we can't test it,
and so it's not science.

01:07:38.060 --> 01:07:39.530
And I just want to go back.

01:07:39.530 --> 01:07:43.460
What we can test is whether or
not our piece of the universe

01:07:43.460 --> 01:07:48.110
happened from inflation,
and we are doing that.

01:07:48.110 --> 01:07:50.190
So what do you do when
you get a cosmic headache?

01:07:50.190 --> 01:07:52.842
Well, you drink a bottle
of multiverse beer.

01:07:52.842 --> 01:07:54.440
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:54.440 --> 01:07:54.950
OK.

01:07:54.950 --> 01:07:56.540
So let me just wrap up here.

01:07:56.540 --> 01:07:59.720
So I talked about our
understanding of the universe,

01:07:59.720 --> 01:08:01.980
and we're very excited about it.

01:08:01.980 --> 01:08:04.580
We know a lot
about the universe,

01:08:04.580 --> 01:08:07.010
but it's predicated on
dark matter, dark energy,

01:08:07.010 --> 01:08:08.270
and inflation.

01:08:08.270 --> 01:08:10.310
And these are mysteries.

01:08:10.310 --> 01:08:15.980
And they all imply
physics or laws of nature

01:08:15.980 --> 01:08:17.270
that we have yet to discover.

01:08:17.270 --> 01:08:20.106
Let me just explain that with
a very complicated diagram.

01:08:20.106 --> 01:08:21.229
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:21.229 --> 01:08:24.020
So I'm just going to be quiet
for a minute or two while you

01:08:24.020 --> 01:08:24.775
read this.

01:08:24.775 --> 01:08:25.970
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:25.970 --> 01:08:26.660
OK.

01:08:26.660 --> 01:08:32.580
So what this is is, this
is an amazing summary

01:08:32.580 --> 01:08:36.930
of what we know about the
world of the subatomic.

01:08:36.930 --> 01:08:41.640
So here you see the word quarks,
and leptons, and everything

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:43.170
we know about it.

01:08:43.170 --> 01:08:45.390
And if you study
this very carefully,

01:08:45.390 --> 01:08:51.229
you will not find in it
dark matter, dark energy,

01:08:51.229 --> 01:08:52.670
or inflation.

01:08:52.670 --> 01:08:54.830
So this is a
tremendous achievement,

01:08:54.830 --> 01:08:57.140
but it doesn't include
dark matter, dark energy,

01:08:57.140 --> 01:08:58.189
and inflation.

01:08:58.189 --> 01:09:01.790
And so that means that our
list of the laws of physics

01:09:01.790 --> 01:09:05.120
and the fundamental pieces of
the universe is incomplete.

01:09:05.120 --> 01:09:07.729
And so this is the
most exciting thing

01:09:07.729 --> 01:09:11.779
that there are deep connections
between the universe,

01:09:11.779 --> 01:09:14.420
the biggest thing
that we can imagine,

01:09:14.420 --> 01:09:16.580
and the elementary particles,
the smallest things.

01:09:16.580 --> 01:09:18.350
That's the purpose
of this picture.

01:09:18.350 --> 01:09:21.340
Here is the sky and these
are a bubble chambers

01:09:21.340 --> 01:09:22.340
of elementary particles.

01:09:22.340 --> 01:09:25.010
So dark matter, when we
figure out what it is,

01:09:25.010 --> 01:09:26.960
it's a new particle
in nature and it

01:09:26.960 --> 01:09:30.710
might tell us how the forces
of nature are unified.

01:09:30.710 --> 01:09:35.880
Dark energy, is it the
energy of nothing or-- oops.

01:09:35.880 --> 01:09:38.006
Yeah, you really do
have bad equipment here.

01:09:38.006 --> 01:09:39.080
[LAUGHTER]

01:09:39.080 --> 01:09:44.240
Or is signaling that something's
wrong with general relativity?

01:09:44.240 --> 01:09:44.960
And so on.

01:09:44.960 --> 01:09:47.060
So we have these
deep connections.

01:09:47.060 --> 01:09:49.160
Figuring out dark
matter is not only

01:09:49.160 --> 01:09:51.410
going to help us
understand the cosmos,

01:09:51.410 --> 01:09:55.730
it's probably going to help us
understand the subatomic world

01:09:55.730 --> 01:09:58.760
and how the forces are unified.

01:09:58.760 --> 01:10:01.130
And we're going to get
clues from a whole bunch

01:10:01.130 --> 01:10:05.840
of experiments, accelerators,
specialize-- this is a detector

01:10:05.840 --> 01:10:06.890
to detect dark matter.

01:10:06.890 --> 01:10:09.080
And you see some
more telescopes here.

01:10:09.080 --> 01:10:12.830
And this is an
extraordinarily exciting time.

01:10:12.830 --> 01:10:15.770
And let me use some pictures
that my daughter helped me

01:10:15.770 --> 01:10:18.590
draw when she was very young.

01:10:18.590 --> 01:10:22.250
So we know much
about the universe.

01:10:22.250 --> 01:10:23.909
So I told you about inflation.

01:10:23.909 --> 01:10:25.700
I mentioned the word
string, so I'm allowed

01:10:25.700 --> 01:10:27.590
to put string cosmology here.

01:10:27.590 --> 01:10:29.840
The Hot Big Bang,
massive neutrinos.

01:10:29.840 --> 01:10:30.800
We have all of this.

01:10:30.800 --> 01:10:33.890
We know a lot, but
we understand less.

01:10:33.890 --> 01:10:38.680
And so the goal is to
put it all together.

01:10:38.680 --> 01:10:41.770
And this is big
stakes, very exciting.

01:10:41.770 --> 01:10:44.302
Because if we think we can put
the picture of the universe

01:10:44.302 --> 01:10:45.760
together, we're
also going to learn

01:10:45.760 --> 01:10:48.820
about the fundamental rules
that govern the universe.

01:10:48.820 --> 01:10:52.830
And so I asked my daughter,
can you help me here?

01:10:52.830 --> 01:10:54.350
What do we got?

01:10:54.350 --> 01:10:56.990
And she said, daddy,
you have an elephant.

01:10:56.990 --> 01:10:58.220
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:58.220 --> 01:11:05.580
And so the metaphor
here, the metaphor

01:11:05.580 --> 01:11:09.900
here is the blind
man and the elephant.

01:11:09.900 --> 01:11:12.930
So we're the blind cosmologists
feeling the universe.

01:11:12.930 --> 01:11:15.420
We feel these different
pieces, but we haven't

01:11:15.420 --> 01:11:16.800
seen the big picture yet.

01:11:16.800 --> 01:11:21.340
And so that's the challenge
for the next generation.

01:11:21.340 --> 01:11:24.150
So it's very, very exciting, and
I thank you for your attention.

